# gen199 — language-as-delta (CODE-MASTERY §7b): F3 SEMANTICS for Python, derived
# by DIFFERENCE from C. The shared expression evaluator is reused unchanged; only
# the concrete syntax is the delta (`def name(params):`, identifier-first params,
# newline-terminated statements). The same `code_eval` answers in both languages —
# one engine, two surfaces — and still refuses honestly when the body is beyond the
# arithmetic evaluator (the F3 deductive/associative boundary §3 exists to measure).
#expect: pass
#faculty: symeval-py
# Single-line def, inline.
> what does add(2, 3) return: def add(a, b): return a + b
< add(2, 3) returns 5
# Operator precedence, inline.
> what does f(2, 3, 4) return: def f(a, b, c): return a + b * c
< f(2, 3, 4) returns 14
# Type-annotated params (a delta from C: the NAME is first, the type follows).
> what does g(4, 5) return: def g(a: int, b: int): return a * b
< g(4, 5) returns 20
# Multi-line file: a local assignment then return, and Python->Python recursion
# (usepy calls addpy and sqpy) — all through the one shared evaluator.
> what does sqpy(6) return in tests/code/py/calc.py
< sqpy(6) returns 36
> what does usepy(4) return in tests/code/py/calc.py
< usepy(4) returns 20
# Honest refusal: a control-flow body is beyond the arithmetic evaluator (yet).
> what does h(1) return: def h(x): return ghost(x)
< cannot compute h(1)